  "prompt": "What is the Lewis dot structure of C2H3Cl?",
  "response": "To draw the Lewis dot structure for **C\u2082H\u2083Cl**, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Determine the total number of valence electrons:**\n   - Carbon (C) has 4 valence electrons.\n   - Hydrogen (H) has 1 valence electron.\n   - Chlorine (Cl) has 7 valence electrons.\n   - Total = (2 \u00d7 4) + (3 \u00d7 1) + 7 = 18 valence electrons.\n\n2. **Arrange the atoms:**\n   - Since carbon is the central atom in most organic molecules, place the two carbon atoms in the center.\n   - Connect the carbons with a single bond.\n   - Attach three hydrogen atoms and one chlorine atom to the carbons.\n\n3. **Distribute electrons to form bonds:**\n   - Draw single bonds between the atoms (C-C, C-H, and C-Cl).\n   - Each bond uses 2 electrons, so the bonds account for 8 electrons (4 bonds \u00d7 2 electrons each).\n\n4. **Assign the remaining electrons:**\n   - Subtract the bonds from the total valence electrons: 18 - 8 = 10 electrons.\n   - Place these as lone pairs on the chlorine atom (Cl needs 3 lone pairs to complete its octet).\n\n5. **Verify the octet rule:**\n   - Each carbon atom has 4 bonds, satisfying the octet rule.\n   - Each hydrogen atom has 1 bond, satisfying the duet rule.\n   - Chlorine has 3 lone pairs and 1 bond, satisfying the octet rule.\n\nThe Lewis dot structure for **C\u2082H\u2083Cl** is:\n\n```\n     H   H\n     |   |\n  H-C-C-Cl\n     |   \n     H\n```\n\nIf double bonds are present, the structure might differ. However, for this molecule, the structure above is valid. Let me know if you'd like further clarification!",
